{
    "publish_date": "2013-09-03T15:04:22.000Z", 
    "score": 7.07321319752764e-05, 
    "video_length": "PT4M9S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "Have you ever noticed", 
            "dur": "1.002", 
            "start": "10.17"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "how the full moon looks bigger", 
            "dur": "1.398", 
            "start": "11.172"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "when it&#39;s near the horizon", 
            "dur": "1.472", 
            "start": "12.57"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "than when it&#39;s high over head?", 
            "dur": "1.934", 
            "start": "14.042"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If so, you&#39;re not alone.", 
            "dur": "1.554", 
            "start": "15.976"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "People have wondered about this strange effect", 
            "dur": "2.2", 
            "start": "17.53"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "since ancient times,", 
            "dur": "1.375", 
            "start": "19.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and surprisingly, we still don&#39;t have", 
            "dur": "2.495", 
            "start": "21.105"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "a great explanation,", 
            "dur": "0.715", 
            "start": "23.6"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but that&#39;s not for lack of trying.", 
            "dur": "2.043", 
            "start": "24.315"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Some of the greatest minds in history -", 
            "dur": "2.268", 
            "start": "26.358"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Aristotle,", 
            "dur": "0.769", 
            "start": "28.626"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Ptolemy,", 
            "dur": "0.689", 
            "start": "29.395"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Da Vinci,", 
            "dur": "0.732", 
            "start": "30.084"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Decartes", 
            "dur": "0.744", 
            "start": "30.816"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "- have all wrestled with this problem", 
            "dur": "1.726", 
            "start": "31.56"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and failed to generate an adequate explanation.", 
            "dur": "3.359", 
            "start": "33.286"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "One of the first ideas suggested", 
            "dur": "1.672", 
            "start": "36.645"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "was that the image of the moon in the sky", 
            "dur": "2.109", 
            "start": "38.317"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "really is bigger near the horizon.", 
            "dur": "2.371", 
            "start": "40.426"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Perhaps the Earth&#39;s atmosphere acts like a giant lens,", 
            "dur": "2.931", 
            "start": "42.797"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "magnifying the moon as it rises and sets.", 
            "dur": "2.615", 
            "start": "45.728"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But this explanation doesn&#39;t cut it.", 
            "dur": "2.337", 
            "start": "48.343"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If anything, the refraction of the atmosphere", 
            "dur": "2.136", 
            "start": "50.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "would make the moon look slightly smaller.", 
            "dur": "2.284", 
            "start": "52.816"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Plus, if you actually measure", 
            "dur": "1.461", 
            "start": "55.1"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the size of the visible moon", 
            "dur": "1.365", 
            "start": "56.561"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "at different positions,", 
            "dur": "2.014", 
            "start": "57.926"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it doesn&#39;t change at all.", 
            "dur": "0.654", 
            "start": "59.94"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But then, why does it still seem bigger", 
            "dur": "1.844", 
            "start": "60.594"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "when it&#39;s rising?", 
            "dur": "1.384", 
            "start": "62.438"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This must be some kind of optical illusion.", 
            "dur": "2.319", 
            "start": "63.822"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The question is, which one?", 
            "dur": "2.066", 
            "start": "66.141"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "One explanation is the Ebbinghaus Illusion,", 
            "dur": "2.906", 
            "start": "68.207"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "where two identical objects look different", 
            "dur": "2.214", 
            "start": "71.113"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because of the relative size", 
            "dur": "1.469", 
            "start": "73.327"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of the objects they&#39;re surrounded by.", 
            "dur": "2.304", 
            "start": "74.796"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Here the two center circles are actually the same size.", 
            "dur": "4.195", 
            "start": "77.1"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Maybe the moon looks bigger near the horizon", 
            "dur": "2.028", 
            "start": "81.295"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because it&#39;s next to tiny trees,", 
            "dur": "1.883", 
            "start": "83.323"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "houses,", 
            "dur": "0.637", 
            "start": "85.206"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and towers in the distance.", 
            "dur": "1.837", 
            "start": "85.843"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But when the moon is higher up,", 
            "dur": "1.463", 
            "start": "87.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it&#39;s surrounded by the vast darkness of the night sky", 
            "dur": "2.505", 
            "start": "89.143"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and looks tiny by comparison.", 
            "dur": "2.48", 
            "start": "91.648"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Another possibility is the famous Ponzo Illusion.", 
            "dur": "2.968", 
            "start": "94.128"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you&#39;ve ever tried to draw in perspective,", 
            "dur": "2.419", 
            "start": "97.096"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you know that the closer something is to the horizon,", 
            "dur": "2.349", 
            "start": "99.515"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the smaller you should draw it.", 
            "dur": "1.954", 
            "start": "101.864"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Our brain compensates automatically for this", 
            "dur": "2.775", 
            "start": "103.818"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "by perceiving objects near the horizon", 
            "dur": "2.113", 
            "start": "106.593"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "as larger than they actually appear.", 
            "dur": "2.17", 
            "start": "108.706"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The two yellow lines in this drawing", 
            "dur": "1.911", 
            "start": "110.876"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "are the same size,", 
            "dur": "1.117", 
            "start": "112.787"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but the upper one seems bigger", 
            "dur": "1.668", 
            "start": "113.904"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because we interpret it as receding", 
            "dur": "1.84", 
            "start": "115.572"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "farther into the horizon.", 
            "dur": "1.63", 
            "start": "117.412"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So, between Ponzo and Ebbinghaus,", 
            "dur": "2.337", 
            "start": "119.042"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it seems like we&#39;ve solved the mystery", 
            "dur": "1.532", 
            "start": "121.379"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of the moon illusion,", 
            "dur": "1.084", 
            "start": "122.911"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but, unfortunately, there are a few details", 
            "dur": "2.38", 
            "start": "123.995"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that complicate things.", 
            "dur": "1.979", 
            "start": "126.375"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "For one thing, if this was just the Ebbinghaus effect,", 
            "dur": "2.967", 
            "start": "128.385"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "then we would expect the moon illusion", 
            "dur": "1.532", 
            "start": "131.352"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to disappear for pilots flying high above the clouds", 
            "dur": "3.228", 
            "start": "132.884"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "since there wouldn&#39;t be any other smaller objects", 
            "dur": "1.954", 
            "start": "136.112"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "near the horizon.", 
            "dur": "1.533", 
            "start": "138.066"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But in fact, pilots and sailors out on the ocean", 
            "dur": "3.004", 
            "start": "139.599"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "still claim to see the moon illusion.", 
            "dur": "2.222", 
            "start": "142.603"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "On the other hand, if it&#39;s just our brain&#39;s autocorrecting", 
            "dur": "2.7", 
            "start": "144.825"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the size of objects near the horizon,", 
            "dur": "2.138", 
            "start": "147.525"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "then we&#39;d expect the moon illusion", 
            "dur": "1.533", 
            "start": "149.663"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to be visible inside a planetarium,", 
            "dur": "2.292", 
            "start": "151.196"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "where the whole sky,", 
            "dur": "0.961", 
            "start": "153.488"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "including the horizon,", 
            "dur": "1.17", 
            "start": "154.449"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is displayed on a spherical dome overhead.", 
            "dur": "3.17", 
            "start": "155.619"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Studies have shown, though,", 
            "dur": "1.641", 
            "start": "158.789"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that this is not the case.", 
            "dur": "1.711", 
            "start": "160.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "To make matters worse,", 
            "dur": "1.116", 
            "start": "162.141"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it seems the moon illusion disappears entirely", 
            "dur": "2.672", 
            "start": "163.257"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "if you just bend over", 
            "dur": "1.082", 
            "start": "165.929"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and look at the moon between your legs.", 
            "dur": "2.06", 
            "start": "167.011"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now, this is just getting ridiculous!", 
            "dur": "2.308", 
            "start": "169.071"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "One of the most promising explanations today", 
            "dur": "2.081", 
            "start": "172.47"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is known as Convergence Micropsia.", 
            "dur": "2.833", 
            "start": "174.551"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Our brains judge the distance to objects", 
            "dur": "2.184", 
            "start": "177.384"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and their apparent size", 
            "dur": "1.54", 
            "start": "179.568"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "by the focus of our eyes.", 
            "dur": "1.956", 
            "start": "181.108"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "When looking at the horizon,", 
            "dur": "1.464", 
            "start": "183.064"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "your eyes focus far off into the distance", 
            "dur": "2.333", 
            "start": "184.528"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "so your brain knows you&#39;re looking far away.", 
            "dur": "2.339", 
            "start": "186.861"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The moon appears a certain size.", 
            "dur": "1.978", 
            "start": "189.2"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Your brain thinks it&#39;s far away,", 
            "dur": "1.682", 
            "start": "191.178"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which it is,", 
            "dur": "0.845", 
            "start": "192.86"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "so you naturally conclude the moon must be big.", 
            "dur": "2.88", 
            "start": "193.705"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But when looking up at the night sky,", 
            "dur": "2.034", 
            "start": "196.585"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "there&#39;s nothing for your eyes to focus on,", 
            "dur": "1.886", 
            "start": "198.619"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "so they default to their rest focus,", 
            "dur": "1.839", 
            "start": "200.505"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which is a point just a few meters away.", 
            "dur": "2.917", 
            "start": "202.344"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now your brain thinks the moon is much closer", 
            "dur": "1.924", 
            "start": "205.261"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "than it really is,", 
            "dur": "1.158", 
            "start": "207.185"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "so you naturally conclude", 
            "dur": "1.087", 
            "start": "208.343"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the moon&#39;s not as big as you thought it was.", 
            "dur": "2.739", 
            "start": "209.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Rather than explain why the moon", 
            "dur": "1.642", 
            "start": "212.169"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "looks so big near the horizon,", 
            "dur": "1.828", 
            "start": "213.811"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Convergence Microspia explains", 
            "dur": "1.793", 
            "start": "215.639"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "why the moon looks so small when overhead.", 
            "dur": "2.88", 
            "start": "217.432"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Still not satisfied?", 
            "dur": "1.813", 
            "start": "220.312"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Well, frankly, neither are many scientists,", 
            "dur": "2.726", 
            "start": "222.125"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "so the debate over the moon illusion still rages on", 
            "dur": "2.99", 
            "start": "224.851"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and may continue as long as we still see it", 
            "dur": "2.505", 
            "start": "227.841"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in the night sky.", 
            "dur": "1.094", 
            "start": "230.346"
        }
    ], 
